ğŸ“– Lesson Content
â€¢ Declaration vs. Affidavit ğŸ“ƒ â€” An affidavit is notarized; a declaration uses the Â§ 1746 perjury statement and usually does not require notarization in federal court. Check state rules for affidavits/notary requirements.
â€¢ Required Elements âœ… â€” Caption & title; declarant identity and personal knowledge; numbered paragraphs; facts (not argument); exhibit references; signature, name printed, date, and the Â§ 1746 sentence.
â€¢ Â§ 1746 Language ğŸ—£ï¸ â€” In the U.S.: â€œI declare under penalty of perjury that the foregoing is true and correct.â€ If outside the U.S.: add â€œExecuted outside the United States.â€ Include execution date and location.
â€¢ Foundation & Authentication ğŸ§± â€” Say how you know: â€œI am custodian/I received this email/I was present.â€ Attach exhibits with labels (Ex. A, Ex. B) and describe them in-text. Fed. R. Evid. 901, 803(6) (business records).
â€¢ Hearsay & Personal Knowledge ğŸ‘‚ â€” Stick to what you saw, did, or received. Quote short portions and attach the document. Identify who said what, when, and how you know.
â€¢ Use Cases ğŸ¯ â€” Support TRO/PI, summary judgment, motions to compel, objections, sanctions, and to create an appeal-proof factual record when hearings are limited or not recorded.
ğŸ“ Assignment
