Tier 2 â€” Lawfare Resistance
Module 26 â€“ Vexatious â‰  Frivolous: Fighting Improper Preâ€‘Filing Labels ğŸš«ğŸ“
âš–ï¸ Core Message
High volume or persistence is not the same as vexatiousness. Courts may restrict access only after notice, a chance to be heard, specific findings that filings are frivolous or harassing, and entry of a narrowly tailored order. Format your opposition to force that analysis.

ğŸ“– Lesson Content
â€¢ Vexatious â‰  Frivolous ğŸ§­ â€” 'Vexatious' is a pattern of filings intended to harass or that are overwhelmingly meritless. A single loss, aggressive litigation, or many filings does not equal vexatious conduct.
â€¢ Due Process First ğŸ”” â€” You are entitled to notice and an opportunity to be heard before any preâ€‘filing restriction or 'vexatious' designation is imposed.
â€¢ Required Findings ğŸ§¾ â€” The court must make **substantive findings** of frivolousness/harassment on the **record**â€”not just conclusions or adjectives.
â€¢ Narrow Tailoring âœ‚ï¸ â€” Any order must be limited in **scope, subject matter, parties, and time**, leave room for legitimate filings, and consider **less drastic alternatives**.
â€¢ Common Tests (Know Your Circuit) ğŸ§ª â€” Examples:
 â€¢ Ninth Circuit (De Long): (1) notice/opportunity; (2) adequate record; (3) substantive findings; (4) narrow tailoring.
 â€¢ Second Circuit (Safir): factors include litigation history, motive, representation status, burden on courts/parties, and adequacy of other sanctions.
â€¢ Strategic Record ğŸ“š â€” Compile your docket history, victories or colorable claims, corrections after clerk feedback, and opponent behavior. Attach an **Exhibit Index** with ECF numbers, dates, and outcomes.
â€¢ Offer Alternatives ğŸ¤ â€” Propose targeted remedies short of a blanket ban: page limits, certification under Rule 11, meetâ€‘andâ€‘confer, leaveâ€‘toâ€‘file for a limited topic, or a short sunset period.
ğŸ“ Assignment
