ğŸ“– Lesson Content
â€¢ Common Patterns ğŸ” â€” Nonâ€‘docketed 'returns'; reâ€‘naming filings to bury them; misâ€‘routing to the wrong case type; issuance delays; 'deficiency' refusals with no cited rule; missing fileâ€‘stamp or received date; portal outages with no alternate path.
â€¢ Proof of Tender ğŸ“¬ â€” Always preserve: mailing receipts, carrier tracking, clerk emails, portal confirmations, timeâ€‘stamped screenshots, and inâ€‘person stamps. Convert each into an exhibit the court can read.
â€¢ Pin the Rule ğŸ“Œ â€” Quote the controlling rule: FRCP 5(d)(4) (clerk must not refuse a filing for improper form), FRCP 79(a) (civil docket), local eâ€‘filing rules, and any administrative orders providing alternate submission methods.
â€¢ Ask for Binary Action ğŸ¯ â€” 'Docket as of received date or issue a deficiency identifying the exact curable defect and the rule.' Never argue by phoneâ€”file the ask with exhibits.
â€¢ Escalation Ladder ğŸªœ â€” (1) Notice of Clerk Communication; (2) Notice of Constructive Denial; (3) Motion to Direct Docketing / to Clarify Docket; (4) Motion to Accept Corrected Filing nunc pro tunc; (5) Mandamus (extraordinaryâ€”only if record shows persistent refusal without basis).
â€¢ Index Everything ğŸ§¾ â€” Keep a running 'Suppression Index' with columns: Date, Event, Actor, Exact Words, Proof (Exhibit), Rule, Requested Cure, Outcome.
ğŸ“ Assignment
